SIMPLE: mime
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mime
<hw>Mime</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mimus</ets>, Gr.
<?/, akin to <?/ to imitate, to mimic: cf. F. <ets>mime</ets>. Cf.
<er>Mimosa</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of drama in which real
persons and events were generally represented in a ridiculous manner; an
ancient Greek or Roman form of farce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An actor in such representations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The art of representing actions, events, situations,
or stories solely by gestures and body movements, without speaking;
pantomime{3}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An actor who performs or specializes in mime{3}; an
actor who communicates entirely by gesture and facial expression; a
pantomime{2}; a pantomimist; a mimer.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mummer, pantomimer, pantomimist.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A mimic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mime
<hw>Mime</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To mimic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
-- <wordforms><wf>Mim"er</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mimeo</ent>⟦br⟧
